k"},"en":{"1281–1359":"1281–1359","1277–1311":"1277–1311","1280–1337":"1280–1337","1282–Male":"1282–Deceased","1289–1353":"1289–1353","–Female":"Deceased","1332–1380":"1332–1380","1257–1289":"1257–1289","1259–1293":"1259–1293","Bef 21 November 1289":"before 21 November 1289","1293":"1293","1282":"1282","1281":"1281","1380":"1380","1280":"1280","1359":"1359","1337":"1337","1259":"1259","before Aug 1277":"before August 1277","1257":"1257","1289":"1289","1311":"1311","1332":"1332","1277":"1277","1353":"1353","about 1332":"about 1332","Anderton with Marbury, Cheshire, England":"Marbury, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Malpas, Cheshire, England":"Malpas, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Egerton, Cheshire, England":"Egerton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"St","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Southern French: variant of   St  .   Romain  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Romain","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Alain, Altagrace, Aurore, Camille, Dominique, Edele, Georges, Henri, Jacques, Jean-Marie, Jean-Michel, Jeanmarie.","French, West Indian (mainly Haiti), and English: variant of   Roman  ."]}]},{"name":"Pierre","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Jacques, Antoine, Yves, Michel, Jean Claude, Mireille, Jean Robert, Francois, Monique, Raoul, Serge.","French, Walloon, West Indian (mainly Haiti), and Mauritian:","from the personal name <i>Pierre</i>, French form of   Peter   (see also below). This is one of the most frequent surnames in Haiti (along with   Jean   and   Joseph  ) and in Saint Martin. It is also established elsewhere in the West Indies (e.g. in Trinidad and Tobago, Saint Lucia, Grenada, and Bahamas)."],"variants":[{"name":"Perrault","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Gisele, Jacques, Marcel, Roch, Alphonse, Andre, Donat, Emile, Francoise, Gaston, Ghislaine.","French: from a pet form of the Old French personal name <i>Perre</i>, a variant of   Pierre  , French form of   Peter  . Compare   Paro  ,   Parro  ,   Parrow  ,   Pearo  ,   Perault  ,   Pero  ,   Perreault  ,   Perro  ,   Perrot  , and   Perrow  .","History: Jacques Perrault/Perrot <i>dit</i> Villedaigre from Mons in Charente-Maritime, France, married Michelle Le Flot in Quebec City, QC, in 1654. Nicolas Perrault/Perrot from Darcey in Côte-d’Or married Madeleine Raclos in QC in 1671. Pierre Perrault from France married Geneviève Duclos in QC <i>c.</i> 1686. François Perrault from Cosne-Cours-sur-Loire in Nièvre married Jeanne-Suzanne Pagé in Quebec City, QC, in 1715. — In North America, this surname was originally (also) a secondary surname or <i>dit</i> (‘also called’) name, borne by Louis Leparon <i>dit</i> Perrault (a son of Pierre Leparon from Derval in Loire-Atlantique, France), who married Marie-Josèphe Normandeau in Quebec City, QC, in 1751. — This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors (along with its altered forms <i>Perrow</i> and <i>Pero</i>) and also in the similar registers of the Huguenot Society of America and of the Huguenot Society of the Founders of Manakin in the Colony of Virginia. The Huguenot ancestor was Charles Perrault from Bordeaux in France, one of the settlers of Manakin, VA, in the early 1700s. However, his descendants bear only altered forms of the surname, such as <i>Perrow</i> and <i>Perow</i>."]},{"name":"Perot","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alphonse, Antoine, Philippe, Remy.","French (<b>Pérot</b>): from a pet form of the Old French personal name <i>Perre</i>, a variant of   Pierre  , French form of   Peter  . Compare   Perrow  .","Altered form of French   Perret  , a cognate of 1 above."]},{"name":"Lapierre","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel, Armand, Andre, Lucien, Normand, Adrien, Alcide, Aristide, Arnaud, Julien, Pierre, Aime.","French, Walloon, and Flemish:","topographic name, with fused French feminine definite article <i>la</i>, for someone who lived on a patch of stony soil or by a large outcrop of rock, from Old French <i>pierre</i> ‘stone, rock’ (compare   Pierre   2); or a habitational name from any of various places called Lapierre or La Pierre in France and Belgium (Wallonia), with the same meaning."]},{"name":"Paret","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Philippe, Pierre.  Spanish Joaquin, Alberto, Caridad, Eduardo, Eugenio, Lourdes, Patricio, Wilfredo.","French: habitational name from (Le) Paret, the name of several places in various parts of France, ultimately derived from Latin <i>paries</i>, genitive <i>parietis</i> ‘wall’ (compare 3 below).","French: from a pet form of the personal name   Pierre  ."]},{"name":"Peregoy","meanings":["Americanized form of French <b>Périgord</b>: habitational name from Périgord, the name of a former province in France, of Gaulish origin.","Alternatively, an Americanized form of northwestern French <b>Périgois</b>, which may possibly be a cognate of 1 above, or, more likely, a regional derivative of the Old French personal name <i>Perre</i>, a variant of   Pierre  , French form of   Peter  . Compare   Pedigo  ,   Perigo  ,   Perrigo  , and   Pherigo  .","History: The progenitor of the Peregoys was Joseph Peregoy, a Frenchman who came to Baltimore County, MD, in 1685. In North America his surname was first recorded as <i>Peregois</i> and later spelled in many other ways, including <i>Perigo</i>, <i>Perigoe</i>, and <i>Perrigo</i>. The majority of his descendants (through his son Henry) bear the surname   Pedigo  ."]},{"name":"Pearre","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre.","Possibly also an altered form of French   Pierre  .","Altered form of English   Perry  ."]},{"name":"Peron","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Cecile, Fernand, Herve, Michel, Philippe, Virginie.","French (<b>Péron</b>): from a pet form of the Old French personal name <i>Perre</i>, a variant of   Pierre  , French form of   Peter  . Compare   Perron   1 and 2.","Breton (<b>Péron</b>, rarely <b>Le Péron</b>): variant of <b>Pédron</b> (see   Pedron  )."]},{"name":"Peter","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Kurt, Otto, Ernst, Fritz, Heinz, Helmut, Horst, Kaspar, Klaus, Siegfried, Wolfgang.","English, Scottish, German, Dutch, French (Alsace and Lorraine), Czech (Moravian), Slovak, Croatian, and Slovenian; Hungarian (<b>Péter</b>): from the personal name <i>Peter</i> (Greek <i>Petros</i>, from <i>petra</i> ‘rock’). The personal name was popular throughout Christian Europe in the Middle Ages, having been bestowed by Christ as a byname on the apostle Simon bar Jonah, the brother of Andrew. The name was chosen by Christ for its symbolic significance (John 1:42, Matt. 16:18); Saint Peter is regarded as the founding head of the Christian Church in view of Christ's saying, ‘Thou art Peter and upon this rock I will build my Church’. In Christian Germany in the early Middle Ages this was the most frequent personal name of non-ancient Germanic origin until the 14th century. In North America, this surname has also absorbed cognates from other languages, for example Czech   Petr  , Polish <b>Piotr</b> and <b>Pietr</b>, Albanian <b>Pjetri</b> (from the personal name <i>Pjetër</i>, definite form <i>Pjetri</i>), and also their derivatives (see examples at   Peterson  ). It has also been adopted as a surname by Ashkenazic Jews."]},{"name":"Perret","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Emile, Jacques, Michel, Andree, Dominique, Etienne, Fernand, Henri, Solange.","French: from a pet form of the Old French personal name <i>Perre</i>, a variant of   Pierre  , French form of   Peter  .","English (Somerset, Gloucestershire and Wiltshire): variant of   Parrott  ."]},{"name":"Patriquin","meanings":["Altered form of French <b>Petrequin</b>: from a pet form of <i>Petre</i>, a regional variant of the personal name   Pierre   ‘Peter’."]}]},{"name":"David","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the greatest of all the kings of Israel, whose history is recounted with great vividness in the first and second books of Samuel and elsewhere. As a boy he killed the giant Philistine Goliath with his slingshot. As king of Judah, and later of all Israel, he expanded the power of the Israelites and established the security of their kingdom. He was also noted as a poet, many of the Psalms being attributed to him. The Hebrew derivation of the name is uncertain; it is said by some to represent a nursery word meaning ‘darling’. It is a very popular Jewish name, but is almost equally common among Gentiles in the English-speaking world. It is particularly common in Wales and Scotland, having been borne by the patron saint of Wales (  see  Dewi   ) and by two medieval kings of Scotland."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When David de St Pierre was born in 1281, in Malpas, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir John de Saint Pierre, was 25 and his mother, Katherine Dutton, was 22. He had at least 1 son with Cecilia. He died in 1359, in Marbury, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 78."},"et":{"1281–1359":"1281–1359","1277–1311":"1277–1311","1280–1337":"1280–1337","1282–Male":"1282–Surnud","1289–1353":"1289–1353","–Female":"Surnud","1332–1380":"1332–1380","1257–1289":"1257–1289","1259–1293":"1259–1293","Bef 21 November 1289":"enne 21. novembrit 1289","1293":"1293","1282":"1282","1281":"1281","1380":"1380","1280":"1280","1359":"1359","1337":"1337","1259":"1259","before Aug 1277":"enne augustit 1277","1257":"1257","1289":"1289","1311":"1311","1332":"1332","1277":"1277","1353":"1353","about 1332":"umbes 1332","Anderton with Marbury, Cheshire, England":"Marbury, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Malpas, Cheshire, England":"Malpas, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Egerton, Cheshire, England":"Egerton, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1281–1359":"1281–1359","1277–1311":"1277–1311","1280–1337":"1280–1337","1282–Male":"1282–Kuollut","1289–1353":"1289–1353","–Female":"Kuollut","1332–1380":"1332–1380","1257–1289":"1257–1289","1259–1293":"1259–1293","Bef 21 November 1289":"ennen vuotta 21. marraskuuta 1289","1293":"1293","1282":"1282","1281":"1281","1380":"1380","1280":"1280","1359":"1359","1337":"1337","1259":"1259","before Aug 1277":"ennen vuotta elokuu 1277","1257":"1257","1289":"1289","1311":"1311","1332":"1332","1277":"1277","1353":"1353","about 1332":"noin 1332","Anderton with Marbury, Cheshire, England":"Marbury, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Malpas, Cheshire, England":"Malpas, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Egerton, Cheshire, England":"Egerton, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1281–1359":"1281–1359","1277–1311":"1277–1311","1280–1337":"1280–1337","1282–Male":"1282–Décédé","1289–1353":"1289–1353","–Female":"Décédée","1332–1380":"1332–1380",